Section1.Para:
Although 4H-SiC power MOSFETs with excellent current rating, breakdown capability, and switching characteristics have been reported [7–9], one of the key issues related to these devices that has been object of scientific discussion over the years is the low value of the inversion channel mobility. Typically, this behavior has been ascribed to the intrinsic nature of the SiO2/SiC system, which exhibits a high density of interface traps (D

                  it
                ) near the conduction band edge [10, 11]. In fact, electron trapping by interface states causes a reduction of the free carriers’ density in the inversion layer, which reduces the channel conductivity. Additionally, the electron mobility in the inversion layer is lowered due to the occurrence of Coulomb scattering both by the trapped charges at interface states and also by the fixed oxide charges [12, 13].
